{{short description|A silica-undersaturated volcanic rock of intermediate composition}}
[[File:Dragon's Teeth (15516917296).jpg|thumb|Benmoreite lava forms the "Dragon's Teeth" landmark on [[Maui]], Hawaii<ref name="MauiGeologyTrip2006">{{cite web | url=http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/gg/resources/docs/Maui_2006.pdf | title=Maui Field Trip | publisher=Department of Geology and Geophysics, University of Hawaii | date=2006 | accessdate=20 November 2018 | author=Sinton, J. | page=12}}</ref>]] 
'''Benmoreite''' is a silica-undersaturated [[volcanic rock]] of [[intermediate composition]]. It is a [[sodium]]-rich variety of [[trachyandesite]] and belongs to the [[Calc-alkaline magma series|alkalic]] suite of [[igneous rock]]s. 

==Nepheline benmoreite==

An origin by [[Fractional crystallization (geology)|fractionation]] from [[basanite]] through [[nepheline]] [[hawaiite]] to nepheline benmoreite has been demonstrated for a volcanic suite in the McMurdo Volcanic Group of late [[Cenozoic]] age in [[McMurdo Sound]] area of Antarctica.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kyle|first1=P. R.|last2=Adams|first2=J.|last3=Rankin|first3=P. C.|title=Geology and petrology of the McMurdo Volcanic Group at Rainbow Ridge, Brown Peninsula, Antarctica|journal=Geological Society of America Bulletin|date=1979|volume=90|issue=7|pages=676–688|doi=10.1130/0016-7606(1979)90<676:GAPOTM>2.0.CO;2|bibcode=1979GSAB...90..676K}}</ref> Nepheline benmoreite magmas derived from [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] sources, containing [[lherzolite]] [[xenolith]]s, display similarities to some [[Plutonic rock|plutonic]] [[nepheline syenite]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Green|first1=D. H.|last2=Edgar|first2=A. D.|last3=Beasley|first3=P.|last4=Kiss|first4=E.|last5=Ware|first5=N. G.|title=Upper mantle source for some hawaiites, mugearites and benmoreites|journal=Contributions to Mineralogy and Petrology|date=1974|volume=48|issue=1|pages=33–43|doi=10.1007/BF00399108|bibcode=1974CoMP...48...33G}}</ref>

